**Explanation:**  
A `debounce` function limits how often a callback function can execute, ensuring it only runs after a specified delay has passed since the last invocation.

```javascript
/**
 * Debounce function to limit the rate at which a function can execute.
 * @param {Function} func The function to debounce.
 * @param {number} delay The delay in milliseconds.
 * @returns {Function} The debounced function.
 */
function debounce(func, delay) {
    let timeoutId;
    return function (...args) {
        clearTimeout(timeoutId);
        timeoutId = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), delay);
    };
}

// Example usage:
window.addEventListener('scroll', debounce(() => {
    console.log('Scrolling stopped!');
}, 300));
```

In this example, the `scroll` event listener will only log `'Scrolling stopped!'` after 300 milliseconds of inactivity, preventing excessive function calls during continuous scrolling.
